-- 003_seed_free_exercise_db_media.sql
-- Hybrid catalog enrichment + extension from free-exercise-db (Unlicense / public domain).
-- Source: https://github.com/yuhonas/free-exercise-db  | images via jsDelivr CDN.
-- (1) enrich existing built-ins with photo + instructions where name+equipment+muscle match exactly.
-- (2) insert net-new gym movements (stretch/SMR/mobility excluded, dups excluded).
-- Idempotent: enrich UPDATEs by id; inserts guarded by lower(name) NOT EXISTS.

update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Leg_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Using a leg press machine, sit down on the machine and place your legs on the platform directly in front of you at a medium (shoulder width) foot stance. (Note: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance described above which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances described in the foot positioning section).$x$,$x$Lower the safety bars holding the weighted platform in place and press the platform all the way up until your legs are fully extended in front of you. Tip: Make sure that you do not lock your knees. Your torso and the legs should make a perfect 90-degree angle. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you inhale, slowly lower the platform until your upper and lower legs make a 90-degree angle.$x$,$x$Pushing mainly with the heels of your feet and using the quadriceps go back to the starting position as you exhale.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and ensure to lock the safety pins properly once you are done. You do not want that platform falling on you fully loaded.$x$] where id='aaaaaaaa-0008-0000-0000-000000000000';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Decline_Barbell_Bench_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and slowly lay down on the bench.$x$,$x$Using a medium width grip (a grip that creates a 90-degree angle in the middle of the movement between the forearms and the upper arms), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. The arms should be perpendicular to the floor. This will be your starting position. Tip: In order to protect your rotator cuff, it is best if you have a spotter help you lift the barbell off the rack.$x$,$x$As you breathe in, come down slowly until you feel the bar on your lower chest.$x$,$x$After a second pause, bring the bar back to the starting position as you breathe out and push the bar using your chest muscles. Lock your arms and squeeze your chest in the contracted position, hold for a second and then start coming down slowly again. Tip: It should take at least twice as long to go down than to come up).$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$,$x$When you are done, place the bar back in the rack.$x$] where id='942a95dc-3ea5-4e19-8739-c1d9f74ad70e';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Decline_Dumbbell_Bench_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.$x$,$x$Once you are laying down, move the dumbbells in front of you at shoulder width.$x$,$x$Once at shoulder width, rotate your wrists forward so that the palms of your hands are facing away from you. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Bring down the weights slowly to your side as you breathe out. Keep full control of the dumbbells at all times. Tip: Throughout the motion, the forearms should always be perpendicular to the floor.$x$,$x$As you breathe out, push the dumbbells up using your pectoral muscles. Lock your arms in the contracted position, squeeze your chest, hold for a second and then start coming down slowly. Tip: It should take at least twice as long to go down than to come up..$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions of your training program.$x$] where id='857a975b-a397-4c3f-8aed-a2e4c7890278';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dumbbell_Flyes/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell on each hand resting on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.$x$,$x$Then using your thighs to help raise the dumbbells, lift the dumbbells one at a time so you can hold them in front of you at shoulder width with the palms of your hands facing each other. Raise the dumbbells up like you're pressing them, but stop and hold just before you lock out. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$With a slight bend on your elbows in order to prevent stress at the biceps tendon, lower your arms out at both sides in a wide arc until you feel a stretch on your chest. Breathe in as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: Keep in mind that throughout the movement, the arms should remain stationary; the movement should only occur at the shoulder joint.$x$,$x$Return your arms back to the starting position as you squeeze your chest muscles and breathe out. Tip: Make sure to use the same arc of motion used to lower the weights.$x$,$x$Hold for a second at the contracted position and repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='77fce924-3881-4ffa-b859-2b86f6710504';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Incline_Dumbbell_Flyes/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Hold a dumbbell on each hand and lie on an incline bench that is set to an incline angle of no more than 30 degrees.$x$,$x$Extend your arms above you with a slight bend at the elbows.$x$,$x$Now rotate the wrists so that the palms of your hands are facing you. Tip: The pinky fingers should be next to each other. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you breathe in, start to slowly lower the arms to the side while keeping the arms extended and while rotating the wrists until the palms of the hand are facing each other. Tip: At the end of the movement the arms will be by your side with the palms facing the ceiling.$x$,$x$As you exhale start to bring the dumbbells back up to the starting position by reversing the motion and rotating the hands so that the pinky fingers are next to each other again. Tip: Keep in mind that the movement will only happen at the shoulder joint and at the wrist. There is no motion that happens at the elbow joint.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='700c09d9-9e68-44ac-842d-1aae525299ea';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Cable_Crossover/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$To get yourself into the starting position, place the pulleys on a high position (above your head), select the resistance to be used and hold the pulleys in each hand.$x$,$x$Step forward in front of an imaginary straight line between both pulleys while pulling your arms together in front of you. Your torso should have a small forward bend from the waist. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$With a slight bend on your elbows in order to prevent stress at the biceps tendon, extend your arms to the side (straight out at both sides) in a wide arc until you feel a stretch on your chest. Breathe in as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: Keep in mind that throughout the movement, the arms and torso should remain stationary; the movement should only occur at the shoulder joint.$x$,$x$Return your arms back to the starting position as you breathe out. Make sure to use the same arc of motion used to lower the weights.$x$,$x$Hold for a second at the starting position and repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='ea16203e-85a0-4a71-9bcf-1511abea12e6';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dumbbell_Bench_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell in each hand resting on top of your thighs. The palms of your hands will be facing each other.$x$,$x$Then, using your thighs to help raise the dumbbells up, lift the dumbbells one at a time so that you can hold them in front of you at shoulder width.$x$,$x$Once at shoulder width, rotate your wrists forward so that the palms of your hands are facing away from you. The dumbbells should be just to the sides of your chest, with your upper arm and forearm creating a 90 degree angle. Be sure to maintain full control of the dumbbells at all times. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Then, as you breathe out, use your chest to push the dumbbells up. Lock your arms at the top of the lift and squeeze your chest, hold for a second and then begin coming down slowly. Tip: Ideally, lowering the weight should take about twice as long as raising it.$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions of your training program.$x$] where id='131ccfd4-abb2-47a7-9e67-c68f6ede76d4';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Pushups/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie on the floor face down and place your hands about 36 inches apart while holding your torso up at arms length.$x$,$x$Next, lower yourself downward until your chest almost touches the floor as you inhale.$x$,$x$Now breathe out and press your upper body back up to the starting position while squeezing your chest.$x$,$x$After a brief pause at the top contracted position, you can begin to lower yourself downward again for as many repetitions as needed.$x$] where id='24ba3e62-0c9a-4cde-bc8d-ed2b4c118a4d';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Pullups/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Grab the pull-up bar with the palms facing forward using the prescribed grip. Note on grips: For a wide grip, your hands need to be spaced out at a distance wider than your shoulder width. For a medium grip, your hands need to be spaced out at a distance equal to your shoulder width and for a close grip at a distance smaller than your shoulder width.$x$,$x$As you have both arms extended in front of you holding the bar at the chosen grip width, bring your torso back around 30 degrees or so while creating a curvature on your lower back and sticking your chest out. This is your starting position.$x$,$x$Pull your torso up until the bar touches your upper chest by drawing the shoulders and the upper arms down and back. Exhale as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: Concentrate on squeezing the back muscles once you reach the full contracted position. The upper torso should remain stationary as it moves through space and only the arms should move. The forearms should do no other work other than hold the bar.$x$,$x$After a second on the contracted position, start to inhale and slowly lower your torso back to the starting position when your arms are fully extended and the lats are fully stretched.$x$,$x$Repeat this motion for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='674be093-7ef8-4572-aca6-1fac33f1dcb4';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Straight-Arm_Pulldown/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$You will start by grabbing the wide bar from the top pulley of a pulldown machine and using a wider than shoulder-width pronated (palms down) grip. Step backwards two feet or so.$x$,$x$Bend your torso forward at the waist by around 30-degrees with your arms fully extended in front of you and a slight bend at the elbows. If your arms are not fully extended then you need to step a bit more backwards until they are. Once your arms are fully extended and your torso is slightly bent at the waist, tighten the lats and then you are ready to begin.$x$,$x$While keeping the arms straight, pull the bar down by contracting the lats until your hands are next to the side of the thighs. Breathe out as you perform this step.$x$,$x$While keeping the arms straight, go back to the starting position while breathing in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='bd99f53c-8db6-432e-9a50-aa49fde62f29';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Band_Pull_Apart/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Begin with your arms extended straight out in front of you, holding the band with both hands.$x$,$x$Initiate the movement by performing a reverse fly motion, moving your hands out laterally to your sides.$x$,$x$Keep your elbows extended as you perform the movement, bringing the band to your chest. Ensure that you keep your shoulders back during the exercise.$x$,$x$Pause as you complete the movement, returning to the starting position under control.$x$] where id='7ed454cc-7681-4f15-bab4-a4f61a550ef3';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Cable_Rear_Delt_Fly/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Adjust the pulleys to the appropriate height and adjust the weight. The pulleys should be above your head.$x$,$x$Grab the left pulley with your right hand and the right pulley with your left hand, crossing them in front of you. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Initiate the movement by moving your arms back and outward, keeping your arms straight as you execute the movement.$x$,$x$Pause at the end of the motion before returning the handles to the start position.$x$] where id='5ef3527e-5660-4458-8c43-930c02681b1f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dumbbell_Shoulder_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$While holding a dumbbell in each hand, sit on a military press bench or utility bench that has back support. Place the dumbbells upright on top of your thighs.$x$,$x$Now raise the dumbbells to shoulder height one at a time using your thighs to help propel them up into position.$x$,$x$Make sure to rotate your wrists so that the palms of your hands are facing forward. This is your starting position.$x$,$x$Now, exhale and push the dumbbells upward until they touch at the top.$x$,$x$Then, after a brief pause at the top contracted position, slowly lower the weights back down to the starting position while inhaling.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='9df1f777-164d-411c-b739-3cacb9d458df';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Face_Pull/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Facing a high pulley with a rope or dual handles attached, pull the weight directly towards your face, separating your hands as you do so. Keep your upper arms parallel to the ground.$x$] where id='2c1f074a-8e54-4ec5-a50a-191bc31043eb';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Preacher_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$To perform this movement you will need a preacher bench and an E-Z bar. Grab the E-Z curl bar at the close inner handle (either have someone hand you the bar which is preferable or grab the bar from the front bar rest provided by most preacher benches). The palm of your hands should be facing forward and they should be slightly tilted inwards due to the shape of the bar.$x$,$x$With the upper arms positioned against the preacher bench pad and the chest against it, hold the E-Z Curl Bar at shoulder length. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you breathe in, slowly lower the bar until your upper arm is extended and the biceps is fully stretched.$x$,$x$As you exhale, use the biceps to curl the weight up until your biceps is fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder height. Squeeze the biceps hard and hold this position for a second.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='3fbb3ef7-8348-4396-9fa7-b6a60d443cca';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/EZ-Bar_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight while holding an EZ curl bar at the wide outer handle. The palms of your hands should be facing forward and slightly tilted inward due to the shape of the bar. Keep your elbows close to your torso. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now, while keeping your upper arms stationary, exhale and curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps. Focus on only moving your forearms.$x$,$x$Continue to raise the weight until your biceps are fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder level. Hold the top contracted position for a moment and squeeze the biceps.$x$,$x$Then inhale and slowly lower the bar back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='aef6db11-3231-42b3-a682-72c37799d868';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Incline_Dumbbell_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Sit back on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand held at arms length. Keep your elbows close to your torso and rotate the palms of your hands until they are facing forward. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While holding the upper arm stationary, curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a second.$x$,$x$Slowly begin to bring the dumbbells back to starting position as your breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='4f7dbad4-5fc0-46cb-ba47-9520f3c444c1';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Cross_Body_Hammer_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight with a dumbbell in each hand. Your hands should be down at your side with your palms facing in.$x$,$x$While keeping your palms facing in and without twisting your arm, curl the dumbbell of the right arm up towards your left shoulder as you exhale. Touch the top of the dumbbell to your shoulder and hold the contraction for a second.$x$,$x$Slowly lower the dumbbell along the same path as you inhale and then repeat the same movement for the left arm.$x$,$x$Continue alternating in this fashion until the recommended amount of repetitions is performed for each arm.$x$] where id='a20eb602-832d-43cd-9732-895318db290f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dumbbell_Bicep_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight with a dumbbell in each hand at arm's length. Keep your elbows close to your torso and rotate the palms of your hands until they are facing forward. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now, keeping the upper arms stationary, exhale and curl the weights while contracting your biceps. Continue to raise the weights until your biceps are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a brief pause as you squeeze your biceps.$x$,$x$Then, inhale and slowly begin to lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='46469cad-5cb7-48a0-98bf-0b4f31fd3b9f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand up with your torso upright while holding a barbell at a shoulder-width grip. The palm of your hands should be facing forward and the elbows should be close to the torso. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While holding the upper arms stationary, curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Tip: Only the forearms should move.$x$,$x$Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder level. Hold the contracted position for a second and squeeze the biceps hard.$x$,$x$Slowly begin to bring the bar back to starting position as your breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='878bf1fc-809f-49d5-af4d-9f457da03abd';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Seated_Leg_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Adjust the machine lever to fit your height and sit on the machine with your back against the back support pad.$x$,$x$Place the back of lower leg on top of padded lever (just a few inches under the calves) and secure the lap pad against your thighs, just above the knees. Then grasp the side handles on the machine as you point your toes straight (or you can also use any of the other two stances) and ensure that the legs are fully straight right in front of you. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you exhale, pull the machine lever as far as possible to the back of your thighs by flexing at the knees. Keep your torso stationary at all times. Hold the contracted position for a second.$x$,$x$Slowly return to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='106e5f2e-5fb9-4749-8dcf-30954b9f40a2';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Lunge/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just below shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.$x$,$x$Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.$x$,$x$Step away from the rack and step forward with your right leg and squat down through your hips, while keeping the torso upright and maintaining balance. Inhale as you go down. Note: Do not allow your knee to go forward beyond your toes as you come down, as this will put undue stress on the knee joint. li>$x$,$x$Using mainly the heel of your foot, push up and go back to the starting position as you exhale.$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the recommended amount of repetitions and then perform with the left leg.$x$] where id='8c1f44a5-1e83-4d7f-8dd8-39f8da584e0d';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Hack_Squat/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Place the back of your torso against the back pad of the machine and hook your shoulders under the shoulder pads provided.$x$,$x$Position your legs in the platform using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Tip: Keep your head up at all times and also maintain the back on the pad at all times.$x$,$x$Place your arms on the side handles of the machine and disengage the safety bars (which on most designs is done by moving the side handles from a facing front position to a diagonal position).$x$,$x$Now straighten your legs without locking the knees. This will be your starting position. (Note: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance described above which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances described in the foot positioning section).$x$,$x$Begin to slowly lower the unit by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up (back on the pad at all times). Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor). Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front. If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.$x$,$x$Begin to raise the unit as you exhale by pushing the floor with mainly with the heel of your foot as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='ebb7813e-54f6-4f04-939d-63ff779a97a5';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Seated_Calf_Raise/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Sit on the machine and place your toes on the lower portion of the platform provided with the heels extending off. Choose the toe positioning of your choice (forward, in, or out) as per the beginning of this chapter.$x$,$x$Place your lower thighs under the lever pad, which will need to be adjusted according to the height of your thighs. Now place your hands on top of the lever pad in order to prevent it from slipping forward.$x$,$x$Lift the lever slightly by pushing your heels up and release the safety bar. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Slowly lower your heels by bending at the ankles until the calves are fully stretched. Inhale as you perform this movement.$x$,$x$Raise the heels by extending the ankles as high as possible as you contract the calves and breathe out. Hold the top contraction for a second.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='f30969dc-9dbe-4ab7-ac25-038cc4c9a579';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Hip_Thrust/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Begin seated on the ground with a bench directly behind you. Have a loaded barbell over your legs. Using a fat bar or having a pad on the bar can greatly reduce the discomfort caused by this exercise.$x$,$x$Roll the bar so that it is directly above your hips, and lean back against the bench so that your shoulder blades are near the top of it.$x$,$x$Begin the movement by driving through your feet, extending your hips vertically through the bar. Your weight should be supported by your shoulder blades and your feet. Extend as far as possible, then reverse the motion to return to the starting position.$x$] where id='961a8018-2ced-49fe-ae20-e22e3b41a6d6';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Hanging_Leg_Raise/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Hang from a chin-up bar with both arms extended at arms length in top of you using either a wide grip or a medium grip. The legs should be straight down with the pelvis rolled slightly backwards. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Raise your legs until the torso makes a 90-degree angle with the legs. Exhale as you perform this movement and hold the contraction for a second or so.$x$,$x$Go back slowly to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='0a5d19e6-b202-4ea0-a4ca-0fe23460fa03';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Plank/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Get into a prone position on the floor, supporting your weight on your toes and your forearms. Your arms are bent and directly below the shoulder.$x$,$x$Keep your body straight at all times, and hold this position as long as possible. To increase difficulty, an arm or leg can be raised.$x$] where id='7bc7e632-2105-4ed9-98d1-b10ebd1ecdc5';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Pallof_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Connect a standard handle to a tower, and—if possible—position the cable to shoulder height. If not, a low pulley will suffice.$x$,$x$With your side to the cable, grab the handle with both hands and step away from the tower. You should be approximately arm's length away from the pulley, with the tension of the weight on the cable.$x$,$x$With your feet positioned hip-width apart and knees slightly bent, hold the cable to the middle of your chest. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Press the cable away from your chest, fully extending both arms. You core should be tight and engaged.$x$,$x$Hold the repetition for several seconds before returning to the starting position.$x$,$x$At the conclusion of the set, repeat facing the other direction.$x$] where id='4d2f5b36-d0e3-4183-bafa-7bd443a1f465';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Cable_Crunch/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Kneel below a high pulley that contains a rope attachment.$x$,$x$Grasp cable rope attachment and lower the rope until your hands are placed next to your face.$x$,$x$Flex your hips slightly and allow the weight to hyperextend the lower back. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$With the hips stationary, flex the waist as you contract the abs so that the elbows travel towards the middle of the thighs. Exhale as you perform this portion of the movement and hold the contraction for a second.$x$,$x$Slowly return to the starting position as you inhale. Tip: Make sure that you keep constant tension on the abs throughout the movement. Also, do not choose a weight so heavy that the lower back handles the brunt of the work.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='f91efefa-3ac0-4b34-95d4-92368d9c97f5';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dead_Bug/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Begin lying on your back with your hands extended above you toward the ceiling.$x$,$x$Bring your feet, knees, and hips up to 90 degrees.$x$,$x$Exhale hard to bring your ribcage down and flatten your back onto the floor, rotating your pelvis up and squeezing your glutes. Hold this position throughout the movement. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Initiate the exercise by extending one leg, straightening the knee and hip to bring the leg just above the ground.$x$,$x$Maintain the position of your lumbar and pelvis as you perform the movement, as your back is going to want to arch.$x$,$x$Stay tight and return the working leg to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat on the opposite side, alternating until the set is complete.$x$] where id='b847815f-df65-4599-a91b-90f7d785dea8';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Wrist_Roller/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$To begin, stand straight up grabbing a wrist roller using a pronated grip (palms facing down). Your feet should be shoulder width apart.$x$,$x$Slowly lift both arms until they are fully extended and parallel to the floor in front of you. Note: Make sure the rope is not wrapped around the roller. Your entire body should be stationary except for the forearms. This is the starting position.$x$,$x$Rotate one wrist at a time in an upward motion to bring the weight up to the bar by rolling the rope around the roller.$x$,$x$Once the weight has reached the bar, slowly begin to lower the weight back down by rotating the wrist in a downward motion until the weight reaches the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the prescribed amount of repetitions in your program.$x$] where id='2c944eb3-b1df-4eef-8327-6acb4ee35b19';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Smith_Machine_Bench_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Place a flat bench underneath the smith machine. Now place the barbell at a height that you can reach when lying down and your arms are almost fully extended. Once the weight you need is selected, lie down on the flat bench. Using a pronated grip that is wider than shoulder width, unlock the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you breathe in, come down slowly until you feel the bar on your middle chest.$x$,$x$After a second pause, bring the bar back to the starting position as you breathe out and push the bar using your chest muscles. Lock your arms in the contracted position, hold for a second and then start coming down slowly again. Tip: It should take at least twice as long to go down than to come up.$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$,$x$When you are done, lock the bar back in the rack.$x$] where id='70837143-2e80-4ef0-a70d-5fc4e1ebac7f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Incline_Push-Up/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand facing bench or sturdy elevated platform. Place hands on edge of bench or platform, slightly wider than shoulder width.$x$,$x$Position forefoot back from bench or platform with arms and body straight. Arms should be perpendicular to body. Keeping body straight, lower chest to edge of box or platform by bending arms.$x$,$x$Push body up until arms are extended. Repeat.$x$] where id='63dc2e07-35ff-4977-9bba-bbd0e9ede757';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Deficit_Deadlift/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Begin by having a platform or weight plates that you can stand on, usually 1-3 inches in height. Approach the bar so that it is centered over your feet. You feet should be about hip width apart. Bend at the hip to grip the bar at shoulder width, allowing your shoulder blades to protract. Typically, you would use an overhand grip or an over/under grip on heavier sets.$x$,$x$With your feet, and your grip set, take a big breath and then lower your hips and bend the knees until your shins contact the bar. Look forward with your head, keep your chest up and your back arched, and begin driving through the heels to move the weight upward. After the bar passes the knees, aggressively pull the bar back, pulling your shoulder blades together as you drive your hips forward into the bar.$x$,$x$Lower the bar by bending at the hips and guiding it to the floor.$x$] where id='60cc794f-ad3f-4d82-a52e-69f91624fcff';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Zottman_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Stand up with your torso upright and a dumbbell in each hand being held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso.$x$,$x$Make sure the palms of the hands are facing each other. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While holding the upper arm stationary, curl the weights while contracting the biceps as you breathe out. Only the forearms should move. Your wrist should rotate so that you have a supinated (palms up) grip. Continue the movement until your biceps are fully contracted and the dumbbells are at shoulder level.$x$,$x$Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the biceps.$x$,$x$Now during the contracted position, rotate your wrist until you now have a pronated (palms facing down) grip with the thumb at a higher position than the pinky.$x$,$x$Slowly begin to bring the dumbbells back down using the pronated grip.$x$,$x$As the dumbbells close your thighs, start rotating the wrist so that you go back to a neutral (palms facing your body) grip.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='b2fa30f9-bdea-423b-9a46-935d37475cfb';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Board_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Begin by lying on the bench, getting your head beyond the bar if possible. One to five boards, made out of 2x6's, can be screwed together and held in place by a training partner, bands, or just tucked under your shirt.$x$,$x$Tuck your feet underneath you and arch your back. Using the bar to help support your weight, lift your shoulder off the bench and retract them, squeezing the shoulder blades together. Use your feet to drive your traps into the bench. Maintain this tight body position throughout the movement.$x$,$x$You can take a standard bench grip, or shoulder width to focus on the triceps. Pull the bar out of the rack without protracting your shoulders. The bar, wrist, and elbow should stay in line at all times. Focus on squeezing the bar and trying to pull it apart.$x$,$x$Lower the bar to the boards, and then drive the bar up with as much force as possible. The elbows should be tucked in until lockout.$x$] where id='cf6baa60-fd5c-4dc3-a3ae-93c7af246265';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Cable_Preacher_Curl/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Place a preacher bench about 2 feet in front of a pulley machine.$x$,$x$Attach a straight bar to the low pulley.$x$,$x$Sit at the preacher bench with your elbow and upper arms firmly on top of the bench pad and have someone hand you the bar from the low pulley.$x$,$x$Grab the bar and fully extend your arms on top of the preacher bench pad. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now start pilling the weight up towards your shoulders and squeeze the biceps hard at the top of the movement. Exhale as you perform this motion. Also, hold for a second at the top.$x$,$x$Now slowly lower the weight to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='b4b22a83-29ac-40c8-a141-517641b5bad4';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Tate_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell in each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.$x$,$x$By using your thighs to help you get the dumbbells up, clean the dumbbells one arm at a time so that you can hold them in front of you at shoulder width. Note: when holding the dumbbells in front of you, make sure your arms are wider than shoulder width apart from each other using a pronated (palms forward) grip. Allow your elbows to point out. This is your starting position.$x$,$x$Keeping the upper arms stationary, slowly move the dumbbells in and down in a semi circular motion until they touch the upper chest while inhaling. Keep full control of the dumbbells at all times and do not move the upper arms nor rest the dumbbells on the chest.$x$,$x$As you breathe out, move the dumbbells up using your triceps and the same semi-circular motion but in reverse. Attempt to keep the dumbbells together as they move up. Lock your arms in the contracted position, hold for a second and then start coming down again slowly again. Tip: It should take at least twice as long to go down than to come up.$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions of your training program.$x$] where id='bab6665f-ebd2-47b5-9497-d820cefb3105';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/JM_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Start the exercise the same way you would a close grip bench press. You will lie on a flat bench while holding a barbell at arms length (fully extended) with the elbows in. However, instead of having the arms perpendicular to the torso, make sure the bar is set in a direct line above the upper chest. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now beginning from a fully extended position lower the bar down as if performing a lying triceps extension. Inhale as you perform this movement. When you reach the half way point, let the bar roll back about one inch by moving the upper arms towards your legs until they are perpendicular to the torso. Tip: Keep the bend at the elbows constant as you bring the upper arms forward.$x$,$x$As you exhale, press the bar back up by using the triceps to perform a close grip bench press.$x$,$x$Now go back to the starting position and start over.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='d88ca09a-3531-4128-9d28-e1bcba5471d4';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Smith_Machine_Squat/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$To begin, first set the bar on the height that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.$x$,$x$Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side (palms facing forward), unlock it and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.$x$,$x$Position your legs using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times and also maintain a straight back. This will be your starting position. (Note: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances discussed in the foot stances section).$x$,$x$Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up. Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor). Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front. If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.$x$,$x$Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel of your foot as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='350f2268-5c88-4e69-b1da-9bb57726ca9a';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Box_Squat/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$The box squat allows you to squat to desired depth and develop explosive strength in the squat movement. Begin in a power rack with a box at the appropriate height behind you. Typically, you would aim for a box height that brings you to a parallel squat, but you can train higher or lower if desired.$x$,$x$Begin by stepping under the bar and placing it across the back of the shoulders. Squeeze your shoulder blades together and rotate your elbows forward, attempting to bend the bar across your shoulders. Remove the bar from the rack, creating a tight arch in your lower back, and step back into position. Place your feet wider for more emphasis on the back, glutes, adductors, and hamstrings, or closer together for more quad development. Keep your head facing forward.$x$,$x$With your back, shoulders, and core tight, push your knees and butt out and you begin your descent. Sit back with your hips until you are seated on the box. Ideally, your shins should be perpendicular to the ground. Pause when you reach the box, and relax the hip flexors. Never bounce off of a box.$x$,$x$Keeping the weight on your heels and pushing your feet and knees out, drive upward off of the box as you lead the movement with your head. Continue upward, maintaining tightness head to toe.$x$] where id='ca07b9c9-8c6f-43a5-b26f-1bc8542bd79f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Single-Leg_Leg_Extension/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Seat yourself in the machine and adjust it so that you are positioned properly. The pad should be against the lower part of the shin but not in contact with the ankle. Adjust the seat so that the pivot point is in line with your knee. Select a weight appropriate for your abilities.$x$,$x$Maintaining good posture, fully extend one leg, pausing at the top of the motion.$x$,$x$Return to the starting position without letting the weight stop, keeping tension on the muscle.$x$,$x$Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.$x$] where id='dbf77a8b-37b4-4ce0-a371-ccb63738bd85';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Narrow_Stance_Leg_Press/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Using a leg press machine, sit down on the machine and place your legs on the platform directly in front of you at a less-than-shoulder-width narrow stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Your feet should be around 3 inches or less apart. Tip: Keep your head up at all times and also maintain the back on the pad at all times.$x$,$x$Lower the safety bars holding the weighted platform in place and press the platform all the way up until your legs are fully extended in front of you. Tip: Make sure that you do not lock your knees. Your torso and the legs should make a perfect 90-degree angle. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you inhale, slowly lower the platform until your upper and lower legs make a 90-degree angle.$x$,$x$Pushing mainly with the heels of your feet and using the quadriceps go back to the starting position as you exhale.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and ensure to lock the safety pins properly once you are done. You do not want that platform falling on you fully loaded.$x$] where id='f47a132f-e1e2-4853-9288-5b1076290758';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Smith_Machine_Calf_Raise/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Place a block or weight plate below the bar on the Smith machine. Set the bar to a position that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step onto the plates with the balls of your feet and place the bar on the back of your shoulders.$x$,$x$Take the bar with both hands facing forward. Rotate the bar to unrack it. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Raise your heels as high as possible by pushing off of the balls of your feet, flexing your calf at the top of the contraction. Your knees should remain extended. Hold the contracted position for a second before you start to go back down.$x$,$x$Return slowly to the starting position as you breathe in while lowering your heels.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='274eeca8-0488-4ee0-a1db-63ec99385eb5';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Standing_Barbell_Calf_Raise/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the bar on the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck).$x$,$x$Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.$x$,$x$Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times as looking down will get you off balance and also maintain a straight back. The knees should be kept with a slight bend; never locked. This will be your starting position. Tip: For better range of motion you may also place the ball of your feet on a wooden block but be careful as this option requires more balance and a sturdy block.$x$,$x$Raise your heels as you breathe out by extending your ankles as high as possible and flexing your calf. Ensure that the knee is kept stationary at all times. There should be no bending at any time. Hold the contracted position by a second before you start to go back down.$x$,$x$Go back slowly to the starting position as you breathe in by lowering your heels as you bend the ankles until calves are stretched.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='dc3ab53b-6a04-486d-9c71-3243c1149c4f';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Decline_Crunch/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down.$x$,$x$Now place your hands lightly on either side of your head keeping your elbows in. Tip: Don't lock your fingers behind your head.$x$,$x$While pushing the small of your back down in the bench to better isolate your abdominal muscles, begin to roll your shoulders off it.$x$,$x$Continue to push down as hard as you can with your lower back as you contract your abdominals and exhale. Your shoulders should come up off the bench only about four inches, and your lower back should remain on the bench. At the top of the movement, contract your abdominals hard and keep the contraction for a second. Tip: Focus on slow, controlled movement - don't cheat yourself by using momentum.$x$,$x$After the one second contraction, begin to come down slowly again to the starting position as you inhale.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='2e9df4ea-b040-4fb6-8d27-fee35fecb2fb';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Jackknife_Sit-Up/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie flat on the floor (or exercise mat) on your back with your arms extended straight back behind your head and your legs extended also. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$As you exhale, bend at the waist while simultaneously raising your legs and arms to meet in a jackknife position. Tip: The legs should be extended and lifted at approximately a 35-45 degree angle from the floor and the arms should be extended and parallel to your legs. The upper torso should be off the floor.$x$,$x$While inhaling, lower your arms and legs back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='4a39ebca-38d8-47ba-ba05-ec51da5ab58c';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Reverse_Crunch/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Lie down on the floor with your legs fully extended and arms to the side of your torso with the palms on the floor. Your arms should be stationary for the entire exercise.$x$,$x$Move your legs up so that your thighs are perpendicular to the floor and feet are together and parallel to the floor. This is the starting position.$x$,$x$While inhaling, move your legs towards the torso as you roll your pelvis backwards and you raise your hips off the floor. At the end of this movement your knees will be touching your chest.$x$,$x$Hold the contraction for a second and move your legs back to the starting position while exhaling.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='4fdf04a3-5455-4fe1-9c87-a5be9557671b';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Plate_Pinch/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Grab two wide-rimmed plates and put them together with the smooth sides facing outward$x$,$x$Use your fingers to grip the outside part of the plate and your thumb for the other side thus holding both plates together. This is the starting position.$x$,$x$Squeeze the plate with your fingers and thumb. Hold this position for as long as you can.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of sets prescribed in your program.$x$,$x$Switch arms and repeat the movements.$x$] where id='a17cd813-cd32-4c4f-9604-94d85473d7d9';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Sled_Row/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Attach dual handles to a sled connected by a rope or chain. Load the sled to an appropriate weight. Face the sled, backing up until there is some tension in the line.$x$,$x$With a handle in each hand, bend the knees slightly, keep your head and chest up, and begin with your arms extended.$x$,$x$To initiate the movement, flex the elbow as you retract your shoulder blades, pulling the sled towards you.$x$,$x$Take a step or two back to get tension in the line and repeat.$x$] where id='3e44e04d-b5df-497b-829c-732a37609440';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Ab_Crunch_Machine/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Select a light resistance and sit down on the ab machine placing your feet under the pads provided and grabbing the top handles. Your arms should be bent at a 90 degree angle as you rest the triceps on the pads provided. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$At the same time, begin to lift the legs up as you crunch your upper torso. Breathe out as you perform this movement. Tip: Be sure to use a slow and controlled motion. Concentrate on using your abs to move the weight while relaxing your legs and feet.$x$,$x$After a second pause, slowly return to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat the movement for the prescribed amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='6013f08f-8c2c-4703-91f2-3fb803f8a603';
update exercises set image_url=$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Dip_Machine/0.jpg$x$, instructions=ARRAY[$x$Sit securely in a dip machine, select the weight and firmly grasp the handles.$x$,$x$Now keep your elbows in at your sides in order to place emphasis on the triceps. The elbows should be bent at a 90 degree angle.$x$,$x$As you contract the triceps, extend your arms downwards as you exhale. Tip: At the bottom of the movement, focus on keeping a little bend in your arms to keep tension on the triceps muscle.$x$,$x$Now slowly let your arms come back up to the starting position as you inhale.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$] where id='6cfb2e77-ac49-45cb-8c8c-723756d6ae51';

insert into exercises (name,muscle_group,secondary_muscles,equipment,exercise_type,instructions,image_url,is_custom,user_id)
select v.name,v.mg::muscle_group,v.sm::muscle_group[],v.eq::equipment_type,v.et::exercise_type,v.ins::text[],v.img,false,null
from (values
($x$3/4 Sit-Up$x$,'core','{}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$Lie down on the floor and secure your feet. Your legs should be bent at the knees.$x$,$x$Place your hands behind or to the side of your head. You will begin with your back on the ground. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Flex your hips and spine to raise your torso toward your knees.$x$,$x$At the top of the contraction your torso should be perpendicular to the ground. Reverse the motion, going only ¾ of the way down.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/3_4_Sit-Up/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Ab Roller$x$,'core','{shoulders}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Hold the Ab Roller with both hands and kneel on the floor.$x$,$x$Now place the ab roller on the floor in front of you so that you are on all your hands and knees (as in a kneeling push up position). This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Slowly roll the ab roller straight forward, stretching your body into a straight position. Tip: Go down as far as you can without touching the floor with your body. Breathe in during this portion of the movement.$x$,$x$After a pause at the stretched position, start pulling yourself back to the starting position as you breathe out. Tip: Go slowly and keep your abs tight at all times.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Ab_Roller/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Advanced Kettlebell Windmill$x$,'core','{glutes,hamstrings,shoulders}','kettlebell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Clean and press a kettlebell overhead with one arm.$x$,$x$Keeping the kettlebell locked out at all times, push your butt out in the direction of the locked out kettlebell. Keep the non-working arm behind your back and turn your feet out at a forty-five degree angle from the arm with the kettlebell.$x$,$x$Lower yourself as far as possible.$x$,$x$Pause for a second and reverse the motion back to the starting position.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Advanced_Kettlebell_Windmill/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Air Bike$x$,'core','{}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$Lie flat on the floor with your lower back pressed to the ground. For this exercise, you will need to put your hands beside your head. Be careful however to not strain with the neck as you perform it. Now lift your shoulders into the crunch position.$x$,$x$Bring knees up to where they are perpendicular to the floor, with your lower legs parallel to the floor. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now simultaneously, slowly go through a cycle pedal motion kicking forward with the right leg and bringing in the knee of the left leg. Bring your right elbow close to your left knee by crunching to the side, as you breathe out.$x$,$x$Go back to the initial position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Crunch to the opposite side as you cycle your legs and bring closer your left elbow to your right knee and exhale.$x$,$x$Continue alternating in this manner until all of the recommended repetitions for each side have been completed.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Air_Bike/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternate Heel Touchers$x$,'core','{}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$Lie on the floor with the knees bent and the feet on the floor around 18-24 inches apart. Your arms should be extended by your side. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Crunch over your torso forward and up about 3-4 inches to the right side and touch your right heel as you hold the contraction for a second. Exhale while performing this movement.$x$,$x$Now go back slowly to the starting position as you inhale.$x$,$x$Now crunch over your torso forward and up around 3-4 inches to the left side and touch your left heel as you hold the contraction for a second. Exhale while performing this movement and then go back to the starting position as you inhale. Now that both heels have been touched, that is considered 1 repetition.$x$,$x$Continue alternating sides in this manner until all prescribed repetitions are done.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternate_Heel_Touchers/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternate Leg Diagonal Bound$x$,'quadriceps','{glutes,calves,hamstrings}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Assume a comfortable stance with one foot slightly in front of the other.$x$,$x$Begin by pushing off with the front leg, driving the opposite knee forward and as high as possible before landing. Attempt to cover as much distance to each side with each bound.$x$,$x$It may help to use a line on the ground to guage distance from side to side.$x$,$x$Repeat the sequence with the other leg.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternate_Leg_Diagonal_Bound/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternating Cable Shoulder Press$x$,'shoulders','{triceps}','cable','strength',ARRAY[$x$Move the cables to the bottom of the tower and select an appropriate weight.$x$,$x$Grasp the cables and hold them at shoulder height, palms facing forward. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Keeping your head and chest up, extend through the elbow to press one side directly over head.$x$,$x$After pausing at the top, return to the starting position and repeat on the opposite side.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternating_Cable_Shoulder_Press/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternating Deltoid Raise$x$,'shoulders','{}','dumbbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$In a standing position, hold a pair of dumbbells at your side.$x$,$x$Keeping your elbows slightly bent, raise the weights directly in front of you to shoulder height, avoiding any swinging or cheating.$x$,$x$Return the weights to your side.$x$,$x$On the next repetition, raise the weights laterally, raising them out to your side to about shoulder height.$x$,$x$Return the weights to the starting position and continue alternating to the front and side.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternating_Deltoid_Raise/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternating Hang Clean$x$,'hamstrings','{biceps,calves,forearms,glutes,back}','kettlebell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Place two kettlebells between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.$x$,$x$Clean one kettlebell to your shoulder and hold on to the other kettlebell in a hanging position. Clean the kettlebell to your shoulder by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebell towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrist as you do so.$x$,$x$Lower the cleaned kettlebell to a hanging position and clean the alternate kettlebell. Repeat.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternating_Hang_Clean/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternating Kettlebell Press$x$,'shoulders','{triceps}','kettlebell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so.$x$,$x$Press one directly overhead by extending through the elbow, turning it so the palm faces forward while holding the other kettlebell stationary .$x$,$x$Lower the pressed kettlebell to the starting position and immediately press with your other arm.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternating_Kettlebell_Press/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Alternating Kettlebell Row$x$,'back','{biceps}','kettlebell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Place two kettlebells in front of your feet. Bend your knees slightly and push your butt out as much as possible. As you bend over to get into the starting position grab both kettlebells by the handles.$x$,$x$Pull one kettlebell off of the floor while holding on to the other kettlebell. Retract the shoulder blade of the working side, as you flex the elbow, drawing the kettlebell towards your stomach or rib cage.$x$,$x$Lower the kettlebell in the working arm and repeat with your other arm.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Alternating_Kettlebell_Row/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Anti-Gravity Press$x$,'shoulders','{back,triceps}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Place a bar on the ground behind the head of an incline bench.$x$,$x$Lay on the bench face down. With a pronated grip, pick the barbell up from the floor. Flex the elbows, performing a reverse curl to bring the bar near your chest. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$To begin, press the barbell out in front of your head by extending your elbows. Keep your arms parallel to the ground throughout the movement.$x$,$x$Return to the starting position and repeat to complete the set.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Anti-Gravity_Press/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Around The Worlds$x$,'chest','{shoulders}','dumbbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Lay down on a flat bench holding a dumbbell in each hand with the palms of the hands facing towards the ceiling. Tip: Your arms should be parallel to the floor and next to your thighs. To avoid injury, make sure that you keep your elbows slightly bent. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Now move the dumbbells by creating a semi-circle as you displace them from the initial position to over the head. All of the movement should happen with the arms parallel to the floor at all times. Breathe in as you perform this portion of the movement.$x$,$x$Reverse the movement to return the weight to the starting position as you exhale.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Around_The_Worlds/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Atlas Stone Trainer$x$,'back','{biceps,forearms,glutes,hamstrings,quadriceps}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$This trainer is effective for developing Atlas Stone strength for those who don't have access to stones, and are typically made from bar ends or heavy pipe.$x$,$x$Begin by loading the desired weight onto the bar. Straddle the weight, wrapping your arms around the implement, bending at the hips.$x$,$x$Begin by pulling the weight up past the knees, extending through the hips. As the weight clears the knees, it can be lapped by resting it on your thighs and sitting back, hugging it tightly to your chest.$x$,$x$Finish the movement by extending through your hips and knees to raise the weight as high as possible. The weight can be returned to the lap or to the ground for successive repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Atlas_Stone_Trainer/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Atlas Stones$x$,'back','{core,quadriceps,biceps,calves,forearms,glutes,hamstrings}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Begin with the atlas stone between your feet. Bend at the hips to wrap your arms vertically around the Atlas Stone, attempting to get your fingers underneath the stone. Many stones will have a small flat portion on the bottom, which will make the stone easier to hold.$x$,$x$Pulling the stone into your torso, drive through the back half of your feet to pull the stone from the ground.$x$,$x$As the stone passes the knees, lap it by sitting backward, pulling the stone on top of your thighs.$x$,$x$Sit low, getting the stone high onto your chest as you change your grip to reach over the stone. Stand, driving through with your hips. Close distance to the loading platform, and lean back, extending the hips to get the stone as high as possible.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Atlas_Stones/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Backward Drag$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,forearms,glutes,hamstrings,back}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Load a sled with the desired weight, attaching a rope or straps to the sled that you can hold onto.$x$,$x$Begin the exercise by moving backwards for a given distance. Leaning back, extend through the legs for short steps to move as quickly as possible.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Backward_Drag/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Backward Medicine Ball Throw$x$,'shoulders','{}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$This exercise is best done with a partner. If you lack a partner, the ball can be thrown and retrieved or thrown against a wall.$x$,$x$Begin standing a few meters in front of your partner, both facing the same direction. Begin holding the ball between your legs.$x$,$x$Squat down and then forcefully reverse direction, coming to full extension and you toss the ball over your head to your partner.$x$,$x$Your partner can then roll the ball back to you. Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Backward_Medicine_Ball_Throw/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Balance Board$x$,'calves','{hamstrings,quadriceps}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Place a balance board in front of you.$x$,$x$Stand up on it and try to balance yourself.$x$,$x$Hold the balance for as long as desired.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Balance_Board/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Ball Leg Curl$x$,'hamstrings','{calves,glutes}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Begin on the floor laying on your back with your feet on top of the ball.$x$,$x$Position the ball so that when your legs are extended your ankles are on top of the ball. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Raise your hips off of the ground, keeping your weight on the shoulder blades and your feet.$x$,$x$Flex the knees, pulling the ball as close to you as you can, contracting the hamstrings.$x$,$x$After a brief pause, return to the starting position.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Ball_Leg_Curl/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Band Hip Adductions$x$,'quadriceps','{}','bands','strength',ARRAY[$x$Anchor a band around a solid post or other object.$x$,$x$Stand with your left side to the post, and put your right foot through the band, getting it around the ankle.$x$,$x$Stand up straight and hold onto the post if needed. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Keeping the knee straight, raise your right legs out to the side as far as you can.$x$,$x$Return to the starting position and repeat for the desired rep count.$x$,$x$Switch sides.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Band_Hip_Adductions/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Ab Rollout$x$,'core','{back,shoulders}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$For this exercise you will need to get into a pushup position, but instead of having your hands of the floor, you will be grabbing on to an Olympic barbell (loaded with 5-10 lbs on each side) instead. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While keeping a slight arch on your back, lift your hips and roll the barbell towards your feet as you exhale. Tip: As you perform the movement, your glutes should be coming up, you should be keeping the abs tight and should maintain your back posture at all times. Also your arms should be staying perpendicular to the floor throughout the movement. If you don't, you will work out your shoulders and back more than the abs.$x$,$x$After a second contraction at the top, start to roll the barbell back forward to the starting position slowly as you inhale.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Ab_Rollout/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Full Squat$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,glutes,hamstrings,back}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just above shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.$x$,$x$Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.$x$,$x$Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder-width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times and maintain a straight back. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees and sitting back with your hips as you maintain a straight posture with the head up. Continue down until your hamstrings are on your calves. Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement.$x$,$x$Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel or middle of your foot as you straighten the legs and extend the hips to go back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Full_Squat/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Incline Shoulder Raise$x$,'shoulders','{chest}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Lie back on an Incline Bench. Using a medium width grip (a grip that is slightly wider than shoulder width), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms straight. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While keeping the arms straight, lift the bar by protracting your shoulder blades, raising the shoulders from the bench as you breathe out.$x$,$x$Bring back the bar to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Incline_Shoulder_Raise/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Rear Delt Row$x$,'shoulders','{biceps,back}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight while holding a barbell using a wide (higher than shoulder width) and overhand (palms facing your body) grip.$x$,$x$Bend knees slightly and bend over as you keep the natural arch of your back. Let the arms hang in front of you as they hold the bar. Once your torso is parallel to the floor, flare the elbows out and away from your body. Tip: Your torso and your arms should resemble the letter "T". Now you are ready to begin the exercise.$x$,$x$While keeping the upper arms perpendicular to the torso, pull the barbell up towards your upper chest as you squeeze the rear delts and you breathe out. Tip: When performed correctly, this exercise should resemble a bench press in reverse. Also, refrain from using your biceps to do the work. Focus on targeting the rear delts; the arms should only act as hooks.$x$,$x$Slowly go back to the initial position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Rear_Delt_Row/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Shrug Behind The Back$x$,'back','{forearms}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight with your feet at shoulder width as you hold a barbell with both hands behind your back using a pronated grip (palms facing back). Tip: Your hands should be a little wider than shoulder width apart. You can use wrist wraps for this exercise for better grip. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Raise your shoulders up as far as you can go as you breathe out and hold the contraction for a second. Tip: Refrain from trying to lift the barbell by using your biceps. The arms should remain stretched out at all times.$x$,$x$Slowly return to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Shrug_Behind_The_Back/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Side Bend$x$,'core','{back}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight while holding a barbell placed on the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck). Your feet should be shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While keeping your back straight and your head up, bend only at the waist to the right as far as possible. Breathe in as you bend to the side. Then hold for a second and come back up to the starting position as you exhale. Tip: Keep the rest of the body stationary.$x$,$x$Now repeat the movement but bending to the left instead. Hold for a second and come back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Side_Bend/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Barbell Squat To A Bench$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,glutes,hamstrings,back}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first place a flat bench or a box behind you. The flat bench is used to teach you to set your hips back and to hit depth.$x$,$x$$x$,$x$Then, set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.$x$,$x$Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.$x$,$x$Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out. Keep your head up at all times as looking down will get you off balance and also maintain a straight back. This will be your starting position. (Note: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance described above which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances discussed in the foot stances section).$x$,$x$Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees and sitting your hips back as you maintain a straight posture with the head up. Continue down until you slightly touch the bench behind you. Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front. If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.$x$,$x$Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel of your foot as you straighten the legs and extend the hips to go back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Barbell_Squat_To_A_Bench/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Battling Ropes$x$,'shoulders','{chest,forearms}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$For this exercise you will need a heavy rope anchored at its center 15-20 feet away. Standing in front of the rope, take an end in each hand with your arms extended at your side. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Initiate the movement by rapidly raising one arm to shoulder level as quickly as you can.$x$,$x$As you let that arm drop to the starting position, raise the opposite side.$x$,$x$Continue alternating your left and right arms, whipping the ropes up and down as fast as you can.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Battling_Ropes/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bear Crawl Sled Drags$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,glutes,hamstrings}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Wearing either a harness or a loose weight belt, attach the chain to the back so that you will be facing away from the sled. Bend down so that your hands are on the ground. Your back should be flat and knees bent. This is your starting position.$x$,$x$Begin by driving with legs, alternating left and right. Use your hands to maintain balance and to help pull. Try to keep your back flat as you move over a given distance.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bear_Crawl_Sled_Drags/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bench Dips$x$,'triceps','{chest,shoulders}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$For this exercise you will need to place a bench behind your back. With the bench perpendicular to your body, and while looking away from it, hold on to the bench on its edge with the hands fully extended, separated at shoulder width. The legs will be extended forward, bent at the waist and perpendicular to your torso. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Slowly lower your body as you inhale by bending at the elbows until you lower yourself far enough to where there is an angle slightly smaller than 90 degrees between the upper arm and the forearm. Tip: Keep the elbows as close as possible throughout the movement. Forearms should always be pointing down.$x$,$x$Using your triceps to bring your torso up again, lift yourself back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bench_Dips/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bench Jump$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,glutes,hamstrings}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$Begin with a box or bench 1-2 feet in front of you. Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Perform a short squat in preparation for the jump; swing your arms behind you.$x$,$x$Rebound out of this position, extending through the hips, knees, and ankles to jump as high as possible. Swing your arms forward and up.$x$,$x$Jump over the bench, landing with the knees bent, absorbing the impact through the legs.$x$,$x$Turn around and face the opposite direction, then jump back over the bench.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bench_Jump/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bench Press with Chains$x$,'triceps','{chest,back,shoulders}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Adjust the leader chain, shortening it to the desired length.Place the chains on the sleeves of the bar.$x$,$x$Lying on the bench, get your head beyond the bar if possible. Tuck your feet underneath you and arch your back. Using the bar to help support your weight, lift your shoulder off the bench and retract them, squeezing the shoulder blades together. Use your feet to drive your traps into the bench. Maintain this tight body position throughout the movement. However wide your grip, it should cover the ring on the bar.$x$,$x$Pull the bar out of the rack without protracting your shoulders. Focus on squeezing the bar and trying to pull it apart. Lower the bar to your lower chest or upper stomach. The bar, wrist, and elbow should stay in line at all times.$x$,$x$Pause when the barbell touches your torso, and then drive the bar up with as much force as possible. The elbows should be tucked in until lockout.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bench_Press_with_Chains/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bench Sprint$x$,'quadriceps','{calves,glutes,hamstrings}','other','strength',ARRAY[$x$Stand on the ground with one foot resting on a bench or box with your heel close to the edge.$x$,$x$Push off with your foot on top of the bench, extending through the hip and knee.$x$,$x$Land with the opposite foot on top of the box, returning your other foot back to the start position.$x$,$x$Continue alternating from one foot to another to complete the set.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bench_Sprint/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent-Arm Barbell Pullover$x$,'back','{chest,shoulders,triceps}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Lie on a flat bench with a barbell using a shoulder grip width.$x$,$x$Hold the bar straight over your chest with a bend in your arms. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$While keeping your arms in the bent arm position, lower the weight slowly in an arc behind your head while breathing in until you feel a stretch on the chest.$x$,$x$At that point, bring the barbell back to the starting position using the arc through which the weight was lowered and exhale as you perform this movement.$x$,$x$Hold the weight on the initial position for a second and repeat the motion for the prescribed number of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent-Arm_Barbell_Pullover/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent-Knee Hip Raise$x$,'core','{}','bodyweight','bodyweight',ARRAY[$x$Lay flat on the floor with your arms next to your sides.$x$,$x$Now bend your knees at around a 75 degree angle and lift your feet off the floor by around 2 inches.$x$,$x$Using your lower abs, bring your knees in towards you as you maintain the 75 degree angle bend in your legs. Continue this movement until you raise your hips off of the floor by rolling your pelvis backward. Breathe out as you perform this portion of the movement. Tip: At the end of the movement your knees will be over your chest.$x$,$x$Squeeze your abs at the top of the movement for a second and then return to the starting position slowly as you breathe in. Tip: Maintain a controlled motion at all times.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent-Knee_Hip_Raise/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent Over Dumbbell Rear Delt Raise With Head On Bench$x$,'shoulders','{}','dumbbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell in each hand and with an incline bench in front of you.$x$,$x$While keeping your back straight and maintaining the natural arch of your back, lean forward until your forehead touches the bench in front of you. Let the arms hang in front of you perpendicular to the ground. The palms of your hands should be facing each other and your torso should be parallel to the floor. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Keeping your torso forward and stationary, and the arms straight with a slight bend at the elbows, lift the dumbbells straight to the side until both arms are parallel to the floor. Exhale as you lift the weights. Caution: avoid swinging the torso or bringing the arms back as opposed to the side.$x$,$x$After a one second contraction at the top, slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.$x$,$x$Repeat the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent_Over_Dumbbell_Rear_Delt_Raise_With_Head_On_Bench/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent Over Low-Pulley Side Lateral$x$,'shoulders','{back}','cable','strength',ARRAY[$x$Select a weight and hold the handle of the low pulley with your right hand.$x$,$x$Bend at the waist until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Your legs should be slightly bent with your left hand placed on your lower left thigh. Your right arm should be hanging from your shoulder in front of you and with a slight bend at the elbow. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Raise your right arm, elbow slightly bent, to the side until the arm is parallel to the floor and in line with your right ear. Breathe out as you perform this step.$x$,$x$Slowly lower the weight back to the starting position as you breathe in.$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and repeat the movement with the other arm.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent_Over_Low-Pulley_Side_Lateral/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent Over One-Arm Long Bar Row$x$,'back','{biceps}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Put weight on one of the ends of an Olympic barbell. Make sure that you either place the other end of the barbell in the corner of two walls; or put a heavy object on the ground so the barbell cannot slide backward.$x$,$x$Bend forward until your torso is as close to parallel with the floor as you can and keep your knees slightly bent.$x$,$x$Now grab the bar with one arm just behind the plates on the side where the weight was placed and put your other hand on your knee. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Pull the bar straight up with your elbow in (to maximize back stimulation) until the plates touch your lower chest. Squeeze the back muscles as you lift the weight up and hold for a second at the top of the movement. Breathe out as you lift the weight. Tip: Do not allow for any swinging of the torso. Only the arm should move.$x$,$x$Slowly lower the bar to the starting position getting a nice stretch on the lats. Tip: Do not let the plates touch the floor. To ensure the best range of motion, I recommend using small plates (25-lb ones) as opposed to larger plates (like 35-45lb ones).$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions and switch arms.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent_Over_One-Arm_Long_Bar_Row/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent Over Two-Arm Long Bar Row$x$,'back','{biceps}','barbell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Put weight on one of the ends of an Olympic barbell. Make sure that you either place the other end of the barbell in the corner of two walls; or put a heavy object on the ground so the barbell cannot slide backward.$x$,$x$Bend forward until your torso is as close to parallel with the floor as you can and keep your knees slightly bent.$x$,$x$Now grab the bar with both arms just behind the plates on the side where the weight was placed and put your other hand on your knee. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Pull the bar straight up with your elbows in (to maximize back stimulation) until the plates touch your lower chest. Squeeze the back muscles as you lift the weight up and hold for a second at the top of the movement. Breathe out as you lift the weight. Tip: Use a stirrup or double handle cable attachment by hooking it under the end of the bar.$x$,$x$Slowly lower the bar to the starting position getting a nice stretch on the lats. Tip: Do not let the plates touch the floor. To ensure the best range of motion, I recommend using small plates (25-lb ones) as opposed to larger plates (like 35-45lb ones).$x$,$x$Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent_Over_Two-Arm_Long_Bar_Row/0.jpg$x$),
($x$Bent Press$x$,'core','{glutes,hamstrings,back,quadriceps,shoulders,triceps}','kettlebell','strength',ARRAY[$x$Clean a kettlebell to your shoulder. Clean the kettlebell to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you raise the kettlebell towards your shoulder. The wrist should rotate as you do so. This will be your starting position.$x$,$x$Begin my leaning to the side opposite the kettlebell, continuing until you are able to touch the ground with your free hand, keeping your eyes on the kettlebell. As you do so, press the weight vertically be extending through the elbow, keeping your arm perpendicular to the ground.$x$,$x$Return to an upright position, with the kettlebell above your head. Return the kettlebell to the shoulder and repeat for the desired number of repetitions.$x$],$x$https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/yuhonas/free-exercise-db@main/exercises/Bent_Press/0.jpg$x$),
